{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Context\nOperation certificates become asymmetric on the foundation substrate (namespace `rebar.opcert.v1`),\nsigned by an environment's Ed25519 key and verifiable by anyone against its public key, binding the\nticket/state so they cannot be replayed. New module `src/rebar/attest/opcert.py`, mirroring\n`attest/authorship.py`, registers `rebar.opcert.v1` in the `registry.py` `POLICY` table pinned to\nthe `sshsig` scheme, and is wired in `attest/__init__.py`.\n\n**Environment-key era rotation (folded in from former task 5893) â€” explicit-SHA model.** Env keys\nlive **out-of-band** (`.rebar/trusted_environments.yaml`, on the code branch, NOT the tickets\nbranch â€” see the epic's \"Trust config & era-validity protocol\"), so the identity epic's\ntickets-branch resolver (`authorship.resolve_event_commit` / `_keyring_for`, which glob\n`<ticket_dir>/<position>-*.json`) **cannot be reused verbatim**. Instead each key record carries\nexplicit `added_at_commit`/`revoked_at_commit` **git SHAs on `main`**. What is reused is the\nera-validity **rule** â€” the `git merge-base --is-ancestor` ancestry comparison and the shared\n`key_not_valid_at_era` verdict â€” factored so authorship (positionâ†’commit) and op-cert\n(explicit-commit) share one ancestry predicate.\n\n**Two-phase verdict (matches `verify_authorship.py`).** Like authorship, the substrate's era check\nreturns a non-verified `Verdict` (`unknown_principal`) when no key is valid at the era; the\n`key_not_valid_at_era` reclassification is done by the **op-cert verifier** (the analog of the\ngate-layer two-phase check): first verify against ANY historical key for the env; if that passes\nbut the era-scoped check fails, emit `key_not_valid_at_era`; otherwise emit `bad_signature`.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Op-certs are produced/verified via the foundation substrate (`src/rebar/attest/opcert.py`,\n      `register_opcert_policy()` pinning `rebar.opcert.v1` â†’ `sshsig` in `registry.POLICY`,\n      registered in `attest/__init__.py`) with an Ed25519 environment key; a test asserts a cert\n      signed by env E verifies against E's public key and fails against a different key.\n- [ ] The certificate subject is an in-toto v1 Statement binding\n      `{ticket id, material fingerprint, merged-log position (a `main` commit SHA)}`; a test asserts\n      a cert cannot be replayed onto a different ticket or onto a mutated material fingerprint.\n- [ ] Environment-key rotation uses the **explicit-SHA** era model: a key is valid at the cert's\n      bound `main` commit `P` iff `is-ancestor(added_at_commit, P)` and not\n      `is-ancestor(revoked_at_commit, P)` (`git merge-base --is-ancestor`), reusing the shared\n      ancestry *rule*, NOT `resolve_event_commit`. The op-cert verifier does the two-phase check\n      (verify against any historical key; if that passes but the era check fails â†’ the shared\n      `key_not_valid_at_era` verdict; else `bad_signature`). A test asserts a cert from a key valid\n      at its era verifies while one past its rotation surfaces `key_not_valid_at_era`."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783969002254510001,"uuid":"3acab98e-5f0f-44a5-a966-e12cc9d90d20"}